It is needless to remark that these manuscript notes ol Leonardo da Vinci can by no possibility have fallen under the eye ol Bacon.

Coming now to writers whom Bacon had read, or may have read, we find H. C. Agrippa (1486-1535), in his De Vanitate Scientiarum (cap. 7, De Dialectica), accusing the Logicians of his time ol either assuming their first principles or accepting them simply on authority, ‘aut ab suo Aristotele, aut abs ali0, qui illa prior dixerit! But, in the same chapter, Agrippa, alter his manner, inveighs also against those sciences which arc founded on the perceptions os the senses

Ludovicus Vives (1492-1540) has some remarks worthy ol Bacon himself on the subject ol Authority. See Praelatio in libros de Disci- plinis (Basle Ed. ol 1555, vol. i. pp. 324, 325). ‘Neque enim effoeta est jam vel exhausta natura, ut nihil prioribus annis simile pariat! ‘Quantum enim ad disciplinas percipiendas omnes aditum nobis inventa superiorum saeculorum aperiunt, et experientia tam diuturna, ut appareat posse nos, si modo applicaremus eodem animum, melius in universum pronunciare de rebus vitae et naturae, quam Aristotelem, Platonem, aut quenquam antiquorum!
